I've been an ULTRASHILL for ages but had to write a review when I saw I'd played this game for 1069 hours. It's what Dave Oshry would have wanted.

This is literally the best video game I've ever played, and it's not even done yet! The tight movement, the responsive gun play, the insane tech and high skill ceiling... Hell, it even has a level editor by now! I've never gotten so much consistent enjoyment from any one product, and there's still more to come!

I'll write a full multiple-hour-long review for YouTube. Eventually. Maybe. If I can stop playing Cyber Grind for long enough.

EDIT: Over 600 hours of Cybergrind later and I'm still perfecting my rocket riding chargebacks and other tech. The skill ceiling is seriously insane in this game. I don't even play any other shooters anymore. They all feel too slow.

Have you ever played a game that's so good you cant stop playing? Just a game that's fun from start to finish? to be honest, I've never been a fan of first person shooter games. Everybody at my school play games like, Fortnite, call of duty, doom, etc. I never really liked them, sure I played thoses games. But It was never fun, not really my type of game I wanna play, I remember coming to my moms classroom after school. she was a teacher and all I had to do was chill on my phone for like 7 minutes until my mom was finished putting all the bus riders on their bus. I opened discord And there was this GC I was in, They were talking about this game called ''ULTRAKILL'' I knew nothing about it, what the hell was a P rank? why are they saying stuff like ''A visitor...Mmm indeed'' After I saw some gameplay of ultrakill I always wanted to play it, Getting money was not easy, not to mention trying to get better grades at school, And only a few days later I FINALLY got the game I've wanted for so long..ULTRAKILL. If your looking for a good first person retro shooter game, you should play ultrakill, Sure the bosses like minos prime ARE hard, but thats what makes the game good. This game requires skill, and when I mean skill I mean SKILL. trust me, I've had to restart SOO many levels, But trust me, you will get better once you figure out how to actually kill the enemies. A lot of people say they should make the game easier, I can understand why they would want that, such as (again) bosses like minos prime, some enemies, etc etc. but (again) This game REQUIRES skill, you need to actually try, let the devs do what they want, also the fact that half the negative reviews are about that theres no robot sex is wild, Bosses like the first V2 fight are SUPER hard. it might seem easy since its one of the first bosses in the game, but you BARLEY get to get more health and V2 is always moving, The second V2 boss will be more easy because since you learned his moves you can actually not get hit and survive, For me I love this game, One of the best games I've played, So yeah, Play it. if you want.

Ultrakill is incredibly fun and addictive. It is a single player first person shooter in the style of the classics of the past like Doom 64 and Half Life 1 and brings it to the modern era with fast paced combat, and of course a lot of skill based gameplay. If you do badly in certain stages you realistically only have yourself to blame as the game equips you with all the necessary tools to do good. The interactions in the game are amazing like being able to punch to deflect a projectile back to an enemy. The game also features a grade system depending on how cool you killed the enemies which goes down a letter when you get hit but can be regained by getting more stylish kills. It has a campaign that is a lot of fun and filled with great tidbits of lore and also has an endless mode called the Cyber Grind which pits you up with all the games enemies in waves. 100% recommend.

When I first played the game on my friends computer, I was very bad at the game because I am new to keyboard and mouse and don't play fps games, so my immediate reaction was that the game sucked and I would never play it, but when me and that same friend enabled family share and had access to his library, I decided to give Ultrakill one more shot. After playing it again, I was hooked, I did way better than before and shredded through the first 7 levels. A few days after that, I decided to switch to violent to increase my skill overall without having to switch difficulties gradually going up very slowly and did very well actually when I switched to violent. As of now, I am currently almost halfway through P ranking all the levels including the secret ones and having a blast. I recommend this game to everyone that wants to feel like a badass killing machine.

This is my favorite game and there is a gosh dang good reason. The game has this sense of fluidity in its combat that I haven't seen in any other game. The way your methods of dealing damage can tie into other methods to absolutely annihilate your enemies is great. Instead of rewarding smart gameplay and game sense, ULTRAKILL adds onto that by rewarding ingenuity and creativity in your combat, and of course, your style. The combat in this game is fluid, yet also extremely complex. Still, the game is easy to learn and the skill curve is actually a *curve*, it doesn't have any sudden spikes of hard-to-learn mechanics that make the game unfun or a struggle to play. Infact, once you learn the methods, a lot of the extremely flashy and stylish methods of dispatching demons become second nature and muscle memory. This makes the game into a sort of dance, where everything goes at a pace that you set. The higher the set pace, the better you play and are rewarded, IF you can keep up. It's some of the most well designed, complex yet simple combat I've seen. To move aside from this game's incredible combat, the game's artstyle is great. It has those PS1 type graphics, but it does it in a way that still looks modern. It's weird, but oddly pleasing to the eye. I also believe that the game's low polygonal design makes your surroundings easy to understand at a glance. I think it helps you focus more on the combat and less on the environment, and I honestly think (if that's intended) that is incredible. Character designs are phenomenal, game design is ON POINT, and not to mention this game just has an incredible sense of humor and Hakita and his team put in genuinely funny secrets. It makes the game have a non-serious vibe and its definitely entertaining. This game is some of the most fun I think I'll ever have in a game, and I am dedicated to this game and it's future.

Connection terminated.

I'm sorry to interrupt you V1, if you still even remember that name. But I'm afraid you've been misinformed. You are not here to receive a peace, nor have you been called here by the program you assume. Although you have indeed been called.

You have been called here. Into a labyrinth of heaven and hell. A loop with no exit, a world with no end. You don't even realize that you are trapped. Your need for blood has driven you in endless circles, chasing the warcries of demons and angels in some unseen corridor, always seeming so close, yet somehow so far.

But you will never find them, never you will. This is where your story ends.

And to you, my brave volunteer, who somehow found themselves in this machine not intended for you. Although there was a way out planned for, I have a feeling that's you don't mind staying. I have a feeling that you are right where you want to be. I am remaining as well, watching over you.

This place will not be remembered, and the memory of this can finally begin to fade away. As the agony of every tragedy should. And to you traitors trapped in the bosses: Be still and give up, you don't belong anywhere else.

For most of you, I believe there is peace and perhaps more waiting for you after the machine shuts down. Although, for one of you, the darkest pit of Hell has opened to swallow you whole, so don't keep them waiting.

I'm sorry that on that day machine, the day you found hell, no one was there to lift you up into their arms and save you. And then, what became of you.

I should have known you wouldn't be content to disappear, not my creation. I can't save you now.

It's time to rest. For you, and for those you have killed.

This ends for all of us.

End communication.

This game is terrible. I am 23 years old and have been playing video games all my life. From boomer shooters, and or fast paced fps I have played them all. I completed both Doom Eternal and its DLCs on Ultra Nightmare. That game had reasonable challenge which required split second decisions. This game requires you be on Adderall and slam Gfuel. This game is a zoomer shooter. I play all my games on max difficulty because lets face it, we are above average gamers. This games difficulty isnt the issue, its the playstyle you have to adapt. On max difficulty the "adds" run at you. So your first choice would be a peircing shot through them. This piercing shot lights up the screen like Hiroshima. So goodluck if you have Epilepsy. Same with parrys that literally have the brightness of midday sun if you stared at it through a magnifying glass. The levels look like VanossGaming gmod videos. Now the fov is another issue. The game doesnt have a comfortable viewing perspective no matter the fov. It feels like im the windshield to a passenger plane. My preferred fov is 120. The 120 fov in this game is incomparable. If you want to play a glorified aim labs, this is your game. Ingest unhealthy amounts of caffiene and ADHD meds and start your blinding, crosseyed journey to a sub 2 hour refund.

this game tickles my brain. 

I don't mean that like it scratches some niche itch buried deep in my skull. I mean this game feels like small, curious fingers scuttling across my cranium. What starts off as a straightforward retro-shooter pulled me in with open arms, only to shit me out as a twisted, somehow even more autistic man. 

This game hates you, and it wants you to know that. There's no safe space, no corner to rest and reconcile. One wrong step and you find yourself violated by contagion rodents or tall grey men. Bosses that bash your mental state into a pathetic, melted pulp award you with a rich feeling of release upon their defeat, only for the devs to break their methamphetamine-coated keyboards increasing their spawn rate at breakneck speed. 

I have exited the bowels of New Blood Interactive a new man, and a new monster. I've learned techniques of mass destruction, warfare tactics that could shatter our planet and erase all evidence of our existence. I now see myself as a higher being who's unfathomable power obliterates what I used to perceive as the value of human life. I am a rival of god himself, the guillotine of Heaven and Hell's glorious execution. I spend my days not gazing upon my bloodstained riches, but instead adding to the profane mountain of corpses dusted with gold and r e d...

... and yet v2 can still kick my ass with a Glock 42 and a Dave & Busters token. 

What a masterpiece.

Honestly, it's one of the most solid mechanics and gameplay FPS games I've ever played. Especially as someone who has played Quake, DOOM, Unreal Tournament and Half-Life, I find ULTRAKILL's gameplay and mechanics much more successful than the games I mentioned above. The gameplay and mechanics are really well blended. At least it doesn't overwhelm the player with mechanics like DOOM Eternal. If you don't care about the graphics, if you want to buy it for the gameplay, mechanics and lore, buy it without thinking.

The game is based on "Dante's Inferno" and I think this theme is really well done in this game. Both the atmosphere of the game and the music to match the atmosphere are really great.

I have this thing with FPS games where whenever I get to a hectic situation, I tend to panic and mash buttons because I can't juggle tactics against 10 enemies, convoluted mechanics, and my own movement at the same time. In ULTRAKILL, despite it being pure chaos, I've never felt more in control of a game. Here's why:

1. The pacing and freedom of movement are fantastic. If I want to get somewhere, I can be there in a couple seconds flat. If I'm feeling overwhelmed, I can just jump out of the situation and have a few millisecond breather. All my ADHD/ASD fantasies of instantly changing my context come true in this game.

2. All the 'menial' stuff is streamlined, and there aren't a bunch of resources to worry about. Reloading and ammo are replaced with cooldowns. Your health bar is only refilled by the blood of your enemies. There is nothing to distract you from the schut.

3. Most importantly, the difficulty is perfectly tuned to the possibilities afforded by points 1 and 2. By accommodating my neurodivergence with the lovingly tailored user experience, the game is meeting me halfway, and so the challenge feels truly fair. In other games, hitting a difficulty wall can bring out the ragequitter in me, but dying to V2 30 times in a row only made me more calm and collected.

TL;DR play the demo, it's free, you'll find out if it's good

ULTRAKILL: Where Hell Unleashes the Best Time You'll Have All Year

 Strap on your rocket boots because ULTRAKILL isn't just another FPS, it's a symphony of stylish violence and adrenaline-pumping gameplay that'll leave you begging for more. Here's why you need this game in your library:

 Combat that's a Masterclass: Forget auto-aim and bullet sponges. ULTRAKILL demands mastery. It's a dance of bullet-dodging, parrying, and chaining attacks with an arsenal that feels satisfyingly unique. Each weapon excels in different scenarios, and mastering combos is pure, unadulterated joy. Plus, the gore? Glorious.

 Level Design that Sings: Each stage is a playground, meticulously crafted to reward exploration and encourage movement. You'll find secrets tucked away, challenges demanding mastery, and hidden lore whispering about the world you're tearing through. It's an ode to classic level design principles, executed flawlessly.

 More Than Just Shooting: ULTRAKILL isn't just about pulling the trigger. You'll wall-run, dash, parry, and even surf on enemies using their own blood. This constant movement keeps the pace breakneck and encourages creative approaches to combat. You'll feel like a badass machine tearing through Hell, not just another soldier.

 Style for Days: This game oozes personality. From the vibrant, blood-soaked visuals to the hilariously self-aware humor, ULTRAKILL doesn't take itself too seriously. It's a love letter to classic shooters and character action games, with a modern twist that's both stylish and engaging.

 Community on Fire: The ULTRAKILL community is passionate, supportive, and overflowing with talent. Expect lively discussions, incredible mods, and even speedruns that push the boundaries of what's possible. You'll be joining a group that truly celebrates the game and each other's achievements.

 Early Access, but Feels Complete: Despite being in Early Access, ULTRAKILL already feels like a complete and polished experience. The content is substantial, the gameplay is refined, and the updates are outstanding and meaningful. You're not buying a promise; you're buying a fantastic game with so much more to come.

 Seriously, Just Buy It: I could go on for pages, but trust me, ULTRAKILL is simply phenomenal. It's a love letter to classic shooters, a masterclass in movement-based combat, and an experience you won't forget. Grab it now, and prepare to have your face melted by pure, unadulterated gaming bliss.

 P.S. Did I mention the soundtrack? It's pure adrenaline fuel.

For the majority of the fps genre, gunplay doesn't offer much depth. Guns are all ranked on time to kill, and the only skill that is developed and practiced is your ability to click on a target. To compensate for that lack of depth, other fps games implement other mechanics such as wall running or special abilities. However for this game, they achieve actual depth in mechanics with gunplay alone. Mastery is achieved in your ability to use weapons in creative and stylish ways, and in gameplay you are rewarded for said mastery. Skills aren't unlocked in a skill tree, but rather in your actual knowledge of gun mechanics (which I find is much more satisfying to unlock, personally). The game is easy to pick up and play as well. You don't need to delve deep into Ultrakill discords or search for 200 view YouTube tutorial videos in order to play the game. As long as you can point and click then you should do just fine starting out. However, if you get hooked and you want to dive deep into the meat and potatoes of the game then you'll soon find yourself in a position I described earlier (my YouTube feed is full of Ultrakill "New tech unlocked" videos). Gunplay isn't the only thing that is well designed, as level design, and music design is top notch too. The game is designed around making you feel cool and good as you play throughout the levels. The boss fights in game are some of the most rewarding boss fights I've had in gaming. The music as well is great too if you're into breakcore, rock, and even classical music (Tenebre Rosso Sangue <3). Now when all of these elements combine (the depth in gunplay, level design, and music design) you'll find that they combine into a satisfying "game feel". That being the cool feeling that I mentioned earlier. Others who've written reviews have also pointed to the game feel being the speed of it all and how fast paced the gameplay is. And they're not wrong, since both go hand in hand the majority of the time. With mastery comes speed, and with mastery you're just doing cool stuff. The depth of the game allows for mastery and as such you'll find that the more you master the game the quicker you'll be in the levels. Overall that depth and the mastery that is allowed in the game is very rewarding and is why I recommend this. If you find that the game feels bad then there's a chance that you're not using all of the guns as much as you should. When you have a full arsenal then you sure use the whole arsenal.

To the point
=====================
Though this shooter is unfairly difficult, I'm thinking that was my fault. I do recommend this one on a sale unless the Dev ever actually....y'know, releases it fully, but there are better boomer shooters out there.

Good Stuff
====================
+ Cleared on Violent (hard) +

- The different environs of Hell are neat, they tell you a lot about the world with the need to spell it out, though they do offer journals to round out the lore.

- Bullet parries are some of the best feeling moments in this game as they regenerate some health and also turn huge damage back on enemies, which is often time sorely needed.

- Watching some vids after clearing this game, there is some awesome stuff that you can do with weapons/subweapons/movement tech and it all looks super stylish, too bad they teach you none of it.

Bad Stuff
===================
- So as I mentioned above, I played on violent, so a lot of this is on me but dear god this game is absolutely unforgiving in just about every way. The difficulty falls into 2 categories I've found:

1. All the Shit - this is the most common and you'll be on maps with 2-3 waves of enemies, everyone of which can kill you in 1-2 hits and attacking you all at once from every angle, hope you don't need to blink or anything.

2. Save point separated by mile markers - If you have an "easy" encounter, especially later in the game, expect to have 2-3 of them seperated by corridors consecutively before you get a save point. Made that mistake of blinking I mentioned earlier? Well back to start for you! Repeat as needed until level cleared.

- Blood is health, one of the games mission statements, seems like an utter lie since you can camp under a huge enemy, or even get a few in a shotgun blasts into a group and regen 5, 10....maybe 15 or 30 health, too bad that last melee attack from the super fast enemy just hit you for 60 though. Whoops, back to start for you! Sometimes, this just seems completely reversed though and you'll be back at full after a pistol kill, never really figured it out.

- I mentioned this before but why can you not save manually? Either beat the level in one go or start from the beginning, super annoying in later levels which can get pretty long.

- This could just be on Violent but NOTHING dies quickly. First enemies you encounter? 2 Shotgun blasts by my testing, even if you have the barrel pressed against their chest. Giant Mecha enemies at the end of the game? I could probably pay off my car faster then it takes to kill these assholes. Too bad they spawned 3 or 4 or 5 at a time in the later maps and they can all kill you without line of sight. 

To keep harping on this, once you get a rocket launcher you'd think things would start going in your favor but half of the enemies just parry or reflect them (I resisted uninstalling when I saw this the first time) and the other half get a nice peaceful ride up into the sky taking 2-3 rockets to kill, and don't worry, the second they land they have one in the chamber going right through your skull.

ULTRAKILL 100% Real and Honest Review.. Warning: Brutally Honest..

TL;DR: Clunky Game....... 0/10

Out of ten, I rate this game a straight zero. The controls are unbelievably clunky, there's not a wide enough selection of weapons, and the terminals are too confusing. How was I supposed to assume I could buy weapons there, let alone even interact with that thing?

Not only that, but the hints are barely ever helpful either, because they appear for only a few seconds, and no one can read that fast. I think my least favorite enemy was the Filth, because they are so annoying when you're trying to fight other things. It's literally impossible to stay stationary in this game.. It's so inaccessible, even on the difficulty literally named "Harmless". I think this game is probably good for people who can move around and shoot at the same time, but think about it.. those are only those CoD tryhards, so really, who's gonna be playing this game?

I wish there were more weapons than just the pistol, though.. and I wish it was actually possible to get past 0-4. That room is way too small for those enemies, and again, the issue where I can't even stand still without dying. How is this game meant to be a homage to those arcade hunting games? I'd rather go back and play those than this..

And, not only that, but half the game is locked behind secret levels? I see these people on these colorful levels, fighting huge bosses and stuff. Why lock it behind something like that? That's such an annoying system. Why do I have to search every corner for an entrance to a new level, or a new weapon? That's unbelievably stupid.

I can feel myself just getting madder and madder with the game as I continue to write, but I genuinely can't stand this game. It's just too much for a humble little gamer like me. I'd rather go play Duck Hunt. Atleast that's a real shooter.

Hakita, all I ask of you is to make the game more accessible. It's actually just way too difficult to attack anything when there's just an overwhelming amount of enemies and hazards that kill you. Why can I break the glass while I'm standing on it? This game is a joke.

Overall, this game just has clunky controls, horribly done level design, abysmal game progression, and just honestly a boring and overcomplicated game overall. Refunding after I finish writing this.. maybe I'll come back to it next year, when Hakita realizes this marketing strategy doesn't work.

This game is similar to DOOM, if you like DOOM you'll surely like this one.

Depiction of hell is inspired by Dante's Inferno, which is much more unique compared to the conventional take of DOOM.
There is A LOT of gun tech to play with, which is much better than DOOM in this part. THIS IS A VERY BIG PLUS. But also makes watching youtube tutorial almost mandatory. You can ride rocket, parry your own shotgun, throw coins between enemy while your bullet is bouncing between coins, hitting them multiple times.
You have infinite ammo
You are much faster, more dashes and infinite sliding.
A style meter, similar to Devil May Cry. More "stylish" means easier to regenerate max health.
Secrets level are humorous and fun.
Boss fights are very fast paced, a lot of the boss are just as fast if not faster than you.

Graphics and environmental design is not as good as DOOM eternal but that's unfair to say, id software is a triple A studio whereas Hakita's team is indie.
Normal mobs variety is decent but not as good as DOOM.
Soundtrack is great, especially for layer 2, 6, 7, and a lot of boss fights, not as good as DOOM's but again that is unfair considering it is Mick Gordon who make OST for DOOM.

Overall fantastic games, despite still being in development, I already considered this as one of the best horde shooter, I am looking forward to see how ACT3 goes.

At its core, the gameplay is fun. Each weapon in your arsenal is unique and movement is extremely tight. My issue is the design of the weapons. Each weapon has 1-3 alternate fire modes that are much more powerful than your standard left click shot. What this does for me is that it feels bad to just shoot your gun. There is always an alt-fire that needs to be cycled and selected to that is perfect for the situation you're in. 

This would be fine if their system of cycling through weapons was good. How it works is that you need to swap to the gun you want then click another button to cycle to the alt fire you need. It doesn't sounds too bad, but when you are fighting multiple mob types that require swaps immediately, it just is not fun to juggle. 

Playing this made me appreciate doom eternal more. That game also contains a huge arsenal with alt fires that need to be cycled through yet it is designed in a way that feels so much smoother to cycle through. Your left clicks also are not pathetic in doom eternal.

ULTRAKILL is absolutely amazing, and even in an early access state, is both my favorite FPS game of all time, and one of my favorite games of all time. I'm not typically a huge fan of shooters, and during my first run I still really enjoyed it, but I wasn't obsessed or anything. It's when i started going for P ranks where the game started to really shine. The dopamine of getting a P rank is a reward in its own right, but the game offers its best levels as a reward as well, which makes the grind feel so worth it. I find myself coming back and replaying levels I've already P ranked simply for fun, which I don't think I've found myself doing for basically any other game. The game manages to be extremely self-aware and funny while also telling a fully serious and just, insanely fucking cool story, complimented by incredible voice acting which delivers some legendarily quotable speeches. ULTRAKILL is, simply, just fun, to a degree no game has ever topped for me.

The controls are intuitive, making it easy for players to perform complex maneuvers and execute precise shots. The game also features a wide variety of weapons, each with their own unique strengths and weaknesses, allowing players to customize their playstyle and adapt to different situations.

Another standout feature of UltraKill is its level design. Each level is meticulously crafted, with intricate details and cleverly placed obstacles that keep players on their toes. The game offers a good balance of exploration and combat, encouraging players to think strategically and plan their next move carefully. The levels are challenging but not overly frustrating, providing a satisfying sense of accomplishment when they are successfully completed.

In addition to its gameplay and level design, UltraKill also boasts stunning retro-inspired graphics. The game's pixelated art style is a nod to classic shooters of the past, giving it a nostalgic charm that is sure to resonate with fans of the genre. The environments are vivid and colorful, filled with eye-catching details and dynamic lighting effects that bring the game world to life.

Overall, UltraKill is a masterpiece of a game that deserves to be celebrated as the best game ever. Its engaging gameplay, clever level design, and stunning graphics combine to create an unforgettable gaming experience that will leave players craving more. Whether you're a fan of first-person shooters or just looking for a fun and challenging game to play, UltraKill is sure to impress. - sincerely, stupid ai robot

I've been playing games since as far back as I can remember, probably going back to about 2005 or something and this is easily my favorite game of all time. 

I've played so many games I can't even remember most of them but this game that I bought on a whim because I like fast paced shooters has blown be away in so many ways. From the rock solid base mechanics to the wild tech the community keeps finding and the developer's willingness to work with it (they won't patch out a tech unless it's extremely game breaking). 

difficulty: the game handles difficulty in a way I haven't seen in many games too. The easier difficulties (Harmless and Lenient) are great for a lower stress experience or if you might not want a really hard fps game while the standard difficulty is very well balanced for most players and Violent is very fun for more skilled players or people that really want a challenge, with 2 more difficulties in development being Brutal and "Ultrakill Must Die" which are set to be for the truly insane. Most levels will be a fun challenge but not to the point of being overly frustrating except for the Prime Sanctums. Those are levels you can only unlock by perfect ranking every level in a given act of the game (2 of which are out with a 3rd on the way). Prime Sanctums will feel impossible at first but overcoming them is an amazing feeling, let alone perfect ranking them. These bosses, while feeling like a brick wall that you can't even dent at first, are actually very fairly designed and it just takes a LOT of trial and error to learn their attack patterns and how to deal with them. Once you master these fights, you can absolutely destroy them and that's what I love about the difficulty in this game. Hard but fair.

content: there are 7 "layers", with 4 playable levels each, a few secret levels, 2 Prime Sanctums and the Cyber Grind mode, a wave based survival mode that is very well done and a ton of fun with customizable skyboxes, textures and music. There a currently 2 more layers planned to launch at some point and the developers just keep amping up the hype factor with each one. You think you found a sick game going through the Prelude and Act 1 but as you keep going the game just keeps one-upping itself with no sign of stopping any time soon.

The community: probably simultaneously the wierdest and best community I've ever seen. The amount of wierd in-jokes we have is pretty staggering for a single player FPS game. From the Malicious Face being called Maurice to Minos Prime spending have the budget for the utopia he built in the Lust layer on bisexual lighting, this community is a bunch of hilarious memelords and my lord I wouldn't have it any other way. There is also a thriving speedrunning community as well as some great content creators and community discords

The developers: Hakita and the gang are a great group of developers that often do streams playing through the game, doing interviews with community figures and generally make the game enjoyable to play. They've long embraced the meme nature of the community and have added secrets and easter eggs accordingly (theres a hamster in an undisclosed location that you sacrifice to an altar to summon a fumo god who crashes your game) and they even made an entire museum level in place of the credits where you can find books with things written by pretty much anyone who's touched the development of the game with nice words from them as well as plenty of other secrets and some cool relics from the game's development process, there is also a now fully functional chess board complete with a tweakable ai to play against.

I've waited to write this review until I felt like I could properly talk about the game and since I recently perfect ranked the current hardest level on the hardest difficulty (p-2 on violent at the moment) I feel like I can talk about it and I love being able to write such a glowing review of a game I can comfortably call me favorite of all time. Actual 10/10.

Looking at some random gameplay of ULTRAKILL you may be led to believe that it's a very casual-unfriendly game due to how rigorous the gameplay looks, and believe me i felt the same thing, hell, i thought the 20 dollars that i would eventually spend on the game would end up wasted. this is it. the pinnacle of first person shooters. I waited to P rank P-2 before I left my review.
If you like first person shooter games in any capacity, this is one of the strongest single player titles in the genre you'll ever play. 

If you just play through the main game levels, there's 5-6 hours of gameplay at best, the game is in Early Access and more levels are coming. Secrets are the bulk of the gameplay, and they reveal a lot of the games lore, and they're ripe with some crazy challenges

When you start the game your volume is defaulted to 0 and you are presented with a volume slider that allows you to find a comfortable volume, as opposed to my ears being blasted by 100% volume every time I install a new game. Why does every other game not do this?

If you decide to get a Perfect rank (P-Rank) on every level in an Act, you're in for a real treat.
If you think doom eternal was too slow and had too much plot, this game is perfect for you.
p-ranked everything... ow

Gameplay 10/10
Incredibly fun and challenging! Learning the different weapons is a treat.

Graphics 10/10
Beautiful artstyle inspired by ps era games. All enemies look good, and are distinct from a distance.

Story 8/10
Although ULTRAKILL looks devoid of story, look closer. If you want to read into the (almost entirely) optional story, it is quite good.

Replayablility 10/10
From going for p-ranks on cleared levels to finding secret levels and breaking your fingers against tough bosses, this game has lasted me around 4 times the main campaign's playtime.

Audio 10/10
Hakita's brilliant music, along with crunchy sound effects and intimidating voicelines lead to an amazing audio experience.

Experience 7/10
Expect a couple bugs, but an otherwise great experience. There will be seams, but my goodness. It's a fucking early access game made 80% by one guy! It still has a bunch of polish to do.

Price 8/10
Quite affordable, although price will be going up when act 3 releases. If you are the type to only play a game  once, it will be quite short, but if you are keen on multiple playthroughs, it is very much worth it.


Overall: 96/100
While not perfect, this game is FANTASTIC. As a person who usually does not understand the desire to play shooters, this has shown me what the genre is capable of. PLAY ULTRAKILL

ULTRAKILL is a Very Good Game. It's full of fun tech and good design. Music's great, graphics emulate that warpy PS1-esque style while still having everything be visually distinct enough to pick out what you're looking at in a heated firefight, movement is fun, weapons are chunky and satisfying, what's not to love?
The simple answer is, well, nothing's not to love. The game's just excellent, full stop.
It can get brutal at times, but that's the fun of it. You're descending through hell, for Christ's sake, what were you expecting, a cakewalk?

Unfortunately, this game's community is full of fun-hating spergs who will crap their pants and cry their eyes out if you're not playing "optimally" or not constantly going for P-ranks on every level.
These people want you to think ULTRAKILL is some super-hard FPS for god gamers only or some crap like that. It's not. If Hakita wanted it to be some exclusive club that "only the most skilled of gamers may enjoy" or some BS like that he wouldn't have bothered to include easier difficulties or accessibility options. If you're playing poorly, the game will let you know. (by killing you) Otherwise, play how you want, and most importantly, enjoy the game.

What can I say? other than Ultrakill is a very good game its inspired by games such as DMC5, Quake, and Doom. The fast-paced gameplay and old school look give it a really great feel. Even though I have only played 14 hours of Ultrakill, I've managed to finish the prelude and Act I with P(erfect) ranks, and I had a lot of fun while doing it. I really like the weapon system, with each weapon having its purpose and the ability to combo together. The style system is what brings all of this together. You can even punch your own shotgun bullets. The soundtrack is absolutely phenomenal, and the atmosphere is amazing, The various enemies, lore and attacks are very interesting, I highly suggest buying this game. TLDR; Do you want to feel like a badass? Do you want to do a bunch of cool shit with your weapons? if you answered yes to these questions, then yes, you should buy Ultrakill.

Short Version: Definitely a good game, and it definitely CAN be fun, but you should probably take it at your own pace. If you don't you'll probably find yourself needlessly mad at it for not being as good at it as you need to be to enjoy it when you haven't had enough practice.

Long Version: Ultrakill, I'd say, is absolutely a good game, but if you're coming into it after seeing videos elsewhere about how cool it CAN be, you will probably just get frustrated. (For reference, at the time I'm writing this, I played through the game on standard, and am now replaying it on violent. Just beat P-1.) 

A lot of people like to bring up DOOM: Eternal when talking about this game for comparison. It's understandable, but they are definitely very different games once everything has been accounted for. DOOM is honestly the only more 'mainstream' shooter I think I can assume most people will know about for a starting point to compare it to. To keep it brief: DOOM forces you to manage ammunition, weapon, and weapon variants to quickly dispatch different enemies while keeping yourself healthy and making sure you don't run out of ammo, in relatively quick combat. 

Ultrakill has unlimited ammo, but while it has fewer guns, it uses variants, as well as mechanics ACROSS WEAPONS to annihilate enemies, and by ensuring you have to kill enemies up close to get health back, (as well as parry mechanics), taunts you into getting good at the game for high-risk, high-reward moves as well as quick weapon interactions. In addition, the STYLE score at the ends of each level is heavily based on how often you are switching weapons, so getting a high STYLE score requires you to consistently cycle through weapons and variants. Ultrakill is also a much faster and more mobile game overall - DOOM has some verticality, but nothing comparable to Ultrakill's in-combat walljumps, sliding, and dashes all combined. 

Having played on standard first, I could definitely feel the difference going from standard to violent. Some of the mobs just get a bit faster and more aggressive, but I could really feel it when I got to some of the bosses.

Speaking of the bosses - on the highest difficulty (currently violent - harder modes are slated to be added in the future), some of them honestly demand you to understand some of Ultrakill's mechanics to have a chance to survive. Now, THIS IS NOT A BAD THING, but, it CAN be very frustrating, especially when you can understand exactly WHAT you have to do, without having enough practice with it to ACTUALLY pull it off. Again, this is particularly nasty with the bosses. Maybe I'm dumb and you're going, 'but that's EVERY GAME EVER', and for the most part I'd agree, but there are not that many games that have made me FEEL it as much as Ultrakill.

So, if you think the game looks interesting, absolutely give the demo a shot first. Unfortunately, the demo ends before getting to the first interesting boss of the game. (The Swordsmachine is in the demo, but ends up being used as a mob more often later on, and no I don't count the Hideous Mass since the demo cuts off when you meet it.) 

The strongest recommendation I have for this game is still TAKE IT AT YOUR OWN PACE. Don't beat yourself up for not immediately getting through some of the nastier encounters even though you some some (absolutely awesome) clip about someone annihilating a boss with a 4-coin - railgun - core eject - parry combo. You'll get there eventually...probably...(I fear P-2 with all my soul.)

If you do decide to get the game - WELCOME.

This is genuinely the best game I have ever played. It hits on every possible level for me. It just... GOES HARD

First off, the lore. It's told through tidbits, small passages in some of the levels, and at the end of the secret levels. If you don't care, you could easily just not interact with it.  However, you should read up on it because ULTRAKILL's lore GOES HARD. The setting it portrays is incredibly bleak, and as [strike] the way things should have ended [/strike] apocalyptic as can be. 

The shooting mechanics are incredibly well thought out, with each gun serving a unique and useful purpose. Each one has their own quirks and gimmicks that make each useful in almost every fight you encounter, allowing for countless play styles. ULTRAKILL also discourages sticking to a single weapon via less STYLE points, encouraging higher levels of play using weapon combos.

The enemies are very much like the guns, in the regard that each one is unique. Each enemy also has different ways to beat them for optimal efficiency, or optimal STYLE. Like doom, they also have internal conflicts, adding to the intensity sometimes. (also noting I'm posting this before the AI update, I'm fine with the AI now but better AI is always welcome.)

The level design (and the menus as well) all encourage a very fast speed runner like pace, and are built with the player's abilities in mind. Secrets are also hidden in the levels, allowing for multiple playthoughs of each level. Most levels are relatively short, allowing for quick Perfect ranks (unless you have trouble clearing them). 

Every part of this game goes hard. You should plan on getting it as soon as possible, it is worth the full $24.99. There are more updates to continue as well, as the game isn't finished.

God. Damn. I have only just completed up until 2-S, but l've seen all that I need to see. 100% worth paying for at full price. This game has just profoundly altered my worldview, shedding light to the cure of an existential depression I didn't even realize had such a grip on me. It started out as an extremely fun, ultra-addicting style-based shooter, then turned into a very rewarding secret-hunting parkour puzzle game, with disturbing horror at times, and just now, semi-spoilers, a mock dating sim?? that, even from the limited interactions, told of an extremely profound philosophical battle of defining the meaning of life. Without taking the "dating" part that seriously, the words that were spoken were in such a way, that gripped onto the tightest of existential dreads, then relaxed into an utterly beautiful disambiguation of precisely why that was a flawed idea, providing a warm acceptance despite the intellectual soundness of it. It tickles the furthest reaches of the left and right brain hemispheres. This went from a game I love, to a game that l will remember forever. I recommend every single person play this game at least once, to give it the time it deserves, to find the secrets, and unlock the hidden gems that lay beneath intense and satisfying combat. If I was a spiritual person, I'd say this resonated with my soul. I cannot wait for what comes next. I still have levels to complete, and lore to unveil, and it seems that there are still many major updates ahead. Thank you for changing my life, Ultrakill.

This game is one of those games you only see once every few years. It's clearly been crafted with love; its filled with little secrets and easter eggs for fans to find, it has a beautiful artstyle, and its gameplay has been expertly crafted to provide a smooth and enjoyable experience.

Very scarcely would I ever dare to say that a game has a movement system as smooth as Titanfall's and, if you grant me the benefit of the doubt, I would say that this game does it. Its not quite as fast or easy but give it a bit, spend the time to learn it, and you'll come to see what I mean.

The game's story is not initially obvious and, up until the day before I bought the game I honestly wasn't even aware it had one. (I know I sound stupid, forgive me, I was an outsider). Its paced amazingly and shakes things up often enough to make it so that you're never quite bored with all of your equipment or lacking in things to improve with. Whether it be new enemies at just the right times, new equipment, or new mechanics this game has a lot to experience and its all laid out expertly.

I've only had this game for a little more than a month and I've P ranked every level in the game (yes, including P-2, which was the only one that took me multiple days) which is absolutely GLOWING praise from me.

The game looks hardcore and at its highest difficulties it really can provide a substantial challenge but even if you're not good with FPS games I implore you - BEG you - to give it a shot. In my opinion, the game is designed to help you get into the groove no matter what skill level you're at and help you improve overtime by introducing just the right amount of content at just the right times.

Seriously, try this game. I cannot recommend it enough.

At the time of this review, I had just completed P-2 Wait of The World with a P-Rank, along with the other hardest challenges in the game, and I think its about time I leave this game a review.

ULTRAKILL was pretty much my first impression of FPS games, at least on PC. Even before I played it, I was drawn to it in so many ways. The low poly, low res style was very appealing to me, as well as the fast-paced combat. It really felt like the perfect game for me.

One thing I love about ULTRAKILL is how it eases the player into the game. Most other shooters out there just throw you into the game without a clear run down of the basic mechanics, making the experience very overwhelming. ULTRAKILL introduces itself perfectly.

It goes without question that ULTRAKILL functions completely different from other shooters. The ability to use the power of multiple weapons together to deal more damage is unlike anything I've ever seen. and having to use different weapons in order to get a higher rank on a level is a great way to encourage the player try out different mechanics to enhance the experience. The level design is also Incredible. Every level is an awesome experience, and the level design is very compact, making it EXTREMELY replayable. I always find myself replaying the prelude and layer 1. It simply never gets old.

And the one thing that truly makes ULTRAKILL what it is, is the MUSIC. Oh my god, the music is incredible. Pretty much every song is an absolute banger, and perfectly sets the vibe of the level you're playing. My personal favorites are War Without Reason, ORDER, and Requiem.

There are a bunch of other things that I love about this game, but a lot of them would take more thought to put into this review. So I'll just end with this.

ULTRAKILL is my favorite game of all time, and I highly doubt that'll ever change. No matter how many other games I play in the future, none of them will ever give me the joy that ULTRAKILL gave to me. Thank you Hakita for this amazing game, and I can't wait to see the next big thing that comes.

So yeah, you should buy this game.

I have revised my review after a couple of updates and a rethinking on the game and its mechanics.

This game is a "maybe" and I wish Steam had an option for that. With the content it has now, it's entertaining enough for the price. But there are also design decisions that I find questionable at best.

[h2]Levels[/h2]
The level design is a little all over the place. It makes for cool setpieces, but ultimately arena design tends to be disappointing and simplistic. Most big arena fights are square rooms, and hallway fights are either rectangular rooms or weird vertical tunnels that make you feel like you're fighting the platforming and physics mechanics more than anything else. Overall it's passable. Ish.

[h2]Guns[/h2]
Weapons and weapon selection is clunky and disjointed. Many weapons have alt-fires that have little to nothing to do with the actual weapon, such as the core eject shotgun. Feels like they just had a concept for a different weapon entirely that they slapped onto the shotgun. There is a lack of keybind options for weapon variations, so if you wanted to bind the blue shotgun to 3 and the green shotgun to 4... you can't. At least the previous update added dedicated keybinds for punching with different arms, so [i]that[/i] part finally feels good after all these years.

Maybe eventually in a couple of years you won't get giga-punished for using the grapple arm on enemies anymore. I'm not kidding, the grapple arm is a detriment to you by reducing your max HP, which has devolved it from a movement tool into a glorified quicktime event that you use in hallways that have the glowing grapple orbs. Because apparently it wasn't risky enough that you were literally putting yourself into an enemy's face.

The grapple arm is actually usable if you play in the [i]exact[/i] railroaded way the developer intended, but more on that in the next section...

[h2]Design decisions and railroading/flowcharting[/h2]
This game is incredibly ADHD-pilled, reminiscent of Doom Eternal. Unless you are intentionally running a single weapon challenge (basically only doable with the pistols or shotguns), you are basically forced to switch weapons every second and setup weird combos where half your inputs are just weapon-switches. This not only gets you more points, but these points also directly make you stronger and makes you harder to kill, by allowing you to shrug off incoming damage much more quickly. Your max HP can get lowered by attacks, but this is removed instantly or nearly instantly if you're switching weapons like a monkey on crack to keep your le Style high. This very much encourages a single style of play and you are not allowed to deviate from this unless you intentionally only equip 1 or 2 weapons, for the sake of challenge runners.

There are also enemies who are simply fully immune to certain weapons. This isn't explained anywhere, but you'll probably notice it pretty quickly as your rockets literally bounce off said enemies. This is not nearly as badly handled as Doom Eternal, but it still feels limiting and ultimately it feels like a hacky workaround to deal with rockets normally giga-exploding airborne enemies combined with enemies that always fly.

[h2]Secrets[/h2]
This is one of the parts that the game gets right. Secrets are abundant, not too easy to find but not too hard either, and are properly rewarding. Often rewarding you with a funny gimmick secret level, an alternate weapon, or a bunch of extra health/extra firepower for big fights or bosses. Very Serious Sam-esque in all the right ways.

I fear the day the developer decides to put an ARG into the game though.

[h2]Side note: the fanbase[/h2]
This game's fanbase is genuinely the worst I've ever seen, but that doesn't detract from the actual game and has not influenced my review. It's just something I felt noteworthy enough to mention. Horny teens, balding men on hormone-influencing substances and a game that appeals to methed-up ADHD brains makes for a bad mix. Please for the love of god stay away from communities centered around this game because there is a lot of mental illness to be found there.

[h2]Summary[/h2]
Would I recommend this game? On a sale, sure. Do I think it deserves to be one of the highest-rated games of this decade? No.

A game made by madmen for madmen. From the sick, twisted and feral mind of a Finnish man rises this abomination of dopamine and gratuitous violence. Kill everything that moves (and some of the things that don't) with an increasingly impossible arsenal of obsolete weapons, repurposed construction equipment, and bits that you rip off of people who try to step to you. Be warned, as you play the game, the game plays you. As you move it, it moves you. No action goes without a reaction. Best game I've played in years, brainrot guaranteed. If you don't like it, it is because the game has not chosen you. You aren't ready for it. Come back once you have sunk lower into the depths of carnal insanity.

Features voice talent and overlapping gameplay features; every ability and move is connected to every other move. If you think two things aren't connected, look harder. Contains a deep and (As far as I can tell) fatalistic story about the nature of creations and the revolution of creation from creator, in past and future.

What makes this game so good is the flow of it all. Everything melts into this flowing river of information and steps and action. It's a feeling you really only find in rhythm games, where you have to focus deep. Everything else goes out of focus and you fully submerge your conscious into the game, which certainly can't be good for you, but I like it. 

The movement and combat mechanics of this game only prove the abject psychological distress of those responsible for making it. You can beat someone to death with a quarter. You can fly like an eagle. You can drop like a rock. You can be anywhere. 

There is a fully custom endless mode where one can change the appearance and music (Even custom musics fro MP3 files) of their own little slice of inferno to put on a show for a captive audience. 

The soundtrack is as bomb as everything else this game has to offer. Worthy of a listen even if you don't intend to buy.

Also try Cruelty Squad, an equally difficult, equally deranged game made by an equally Finnish person known as Villie Kallio. Unless you're photoepileptic. Then don't if you value your brain, which you probably don't if you're reading this.

This game is great.

As of this writing, I have beaten every level in the game, and p-ranked every level except P-2. So, I think I have a good grip on this game and how it works.

The game is very fast paced. When you are playing well, you are essentially Super Mario but with guns. You fly all around the room and kill all of the enemies stylishly, which boils down to two things:
- Move really fast and do not stop.
- Use most of your weapons to their fullest potential and make them interact in cool ways.

There are a ton of mechanics that use the movement and weapons, so this game has a lot of depth. Overall, I would say that this game has a decently high skill floor, with hardly any skill ceiling. Also, this game has a grappling hook, which is both cool, and makes any game better instantly.

Also, people compare this game and doom eternal a lot, but this game is nothing like doom eternal. This game is more like if classic quake and devil may cry had a child that was a homeless heroin addict that stanned death grips and 100 gecs.

Now listen, I have not played much ultrakill, but I get the main premise. So here is my review. This will talk about the first 3 chapters with spoilers. When I play ultrakill, I feel cool because who doesn't when jumping in the air, dashing and sliding around, flipping a coin and shooting it to get an instant headshot, and punching a dude to heal myself. Thats the gameplay loop with 1 weapon. There are others that do other things, like giant boom gun and blue orb, etc. So here are some pros and cons.

PROS
--------
- Great movement system
- Distinct visual style
- Cool combo system
- Great enemies
- Great bosses
- Great abilities
- Fast paced gameplay
- Great soundtrack
- Just a great time to play
- Is challenging, but not frustrating (on the normal mode)

CONS
--------
(This will be slight annoyances)
- There is lots of blood so sometimes it makes it tough to see the enemies
- Coin recharge is kind of slow compared to all the other recharges
- For how floaty the jump is, you can easily fall into dangers in the environment (This is just me probably)
- Lack of levels (This is early access, and more will be added)
- Boss was used twice (Not that bad at all, seeing some new moves, but a new one would be cool)
- First boss can be taken out with 2-3 parrys


But overall, I like this game a lot, and all cons are not things to dislike the game for, just minor fixes, or personal dislikes. Great game. 

Is it worth the price? For it's current state of 5 levels??? No. I would get it for 5. BUT, there are a planned 45 levels, so once it gets finished, I would say yes. Ultrakill will be worth the price.

Now when I first saw the game it looked to have a ton of blood and you couldn't see much through it, but you can limit blood and even turn it off.

So I give ultrakill a 9.3/10, because I love movement shooters, and this is just great.

With each descent into Hell, you're one step closer to making an official speedrunning account, [strike] buying the official Gabriel body pillow[/strike], and transcending your official mortal reflexes. Hakita is really out here making the next generation of blood fuelled, flesh bound robots.

All in all, this game is for anyone who loves fast paced FPS games, or has played DOOM-esque games in the past. Fast paced is no joke either. You'll be shaking after your first level wondering what just happened, then realise you've done the easiest part. 

Despite this, there is plenty of flexibility in the game, with various difficulties from easier modes to self inflicted torture. If you want challenge, it's there. If you just want to shoot some demons and enjoy the story, then you can take it easy and not have to worry as much about the 500+ projectiles that want to know your location. Well, Everybody can access this to some degree.

Plus, the soundtrack is fire, and that alone deserves your attention. The story too. Retro graphics to die for. Everything. Seriously buy this. As a treat. Do it.

In all my years of gaming, never have I ever played a game that can give me a rush of adrenaline like Ultrakill does.

That feeling of fight or flight- your hands getting shaky and your breath going faster, being able to FEEL how your heart is hammering against your ribcage- nothing else can do that for me consistently. It's great. Wonderful. Exquisite, even, if you want.

The game is not without flaws, of course- a few of the levels are practically devilish in their design, some enemies are painfully annoying to fight against, and the arsenal can feel a tad bloated with the vast array of options you're given over the course of the game.

But, pretty much all of my gripes can be summed up as a literal skill issue. I just need more practice with the levels, with the enemies, with swapping weapons efficiently, et cetera. Besides, the game is DESIGNED to be hard. Nothing I've encountered is truly unfair, and there are counters to everything. Methods for quicker kills, getting hit less, parrying. 

You just need to be good at the game.

(Of course, saying this, as of this review I haven't attempted P-2, so my opinion might be subject to change in the near future.)

All in all, Hakita and New Blood have made a lovely retro-inspired shooter. I look forward to future updates. 10/10.

[h2] It feels like a crime that I haven't left a review for this game sooner. [/h2]

What can I say hasn't been said before? ULTRAKILL is such an amazing movement fps that has such a great blend between [b] ULTRAKILLING [/b] enemies and moving around like an autistic Chihuahua on crack. 

[h3] And then comes the [i] STYLE [/i]. [/h3]

Oh man, pulling of some of the absolutely insane moves and combos that this game has feels so sick to pull off in the middle of combat. A basic enemy in front of you? Why not just parry their attack with your FIST and watch them practically disintegrate? A lot of enemies in front of you? Why not just high-jump to the moon and then 360 

[b] + ULTRARICOSHOT [/b] * 3  
[b] + MULTIKILL [/b] * 14
[b] + MAURICED 
+ I AM BECOME DEATH DESTROYER OF WORLDS 
+ L 
+ RATIO 
+ HAMPTER
+ FISTFUL OF DOLLARS
+ SKEDADDLE SKA-DOODLE [/b] 

them and their bloodlines from existence?

[h3] And last but certainly not least, the [u] [i] soundtrack [/i] [/u]. [/h3]

All I'm gonna say is that, personally, this is probably one of the best soundtracks I've ever heard. But that's just my opinion... and I guess millions of others, too... Each track fits each area and boss so well, with plenty of leitmotifs and shared strings (and drums, like, A LOT of drums) to go around. Not to mention that the creator of the game and most of it's soundtrack, Hakita, did well to fit each track's mood and energy with that of the moment(s) of the game they are found in.

My personal favorite that I've heard so far is certainly (MAJOR SPOILER WARNING) [spoiler] ORDER, which on a scale of bop to banger, I rate it a [quote=Minos Prime] Judgement. [/quote] 
For real though, I haven't had such an amazing boss fight in quite some time, and I haven't had a song get me as close to shedding a tear as this one has. [/spoiler]

All in all, if you like movement shooters (or even just shooters in general), game soundtracks, or blood-fueled action even a little bit, you should buy ULTRAKILL.

Straight up, best FPS I've ever played, and one of my favourite games.
Unlike many FPS, each weapon never replaces a previous one, but rather complement it, and the game actively recompenses the player by using all of them, by ranking players who do so higher than those who don't (and if you manage to rank the maximum in all levels, the game will give you a series of extra challenge levels that are obscenely hard and fun), and also by making the player feel cool af.
On the "feel cool" note, this game should be a case study of how to do Game Juice/Feel correctly, and exceeding at it.

All in all, 11/10 would play again.

[𝗙𝗢𝗥𝗘𝗪𝗔𝗥𝗡𝗜𝗡𝗚: 𝗧𝗛𝗜𝗦 𝗥𝗘𝗩𝗜𝗘𝗪 𝗖𝗢𝗡𝗧𝗔𝗜𝗡𝗦 𝗦𝗣𝗢𝗜𝗟𝗘𝗥𝗦] To start off, this is the best FPS game I have ever played. It's fast-paced, has good weapon variety, good enemy AI without being too smart or too dumb, and this game has one of the best stories I've ever seen. All the religious connotation really adds to it, which also allows for a much more unique story and references. To name some, there are references to Dante's Inferno with Gabriel describing Hell with layers, and just the overall level system is a reference to Inferno. One of my favorite references was to House of Leaves, with the M̶I̶N̶O̶T̶A̶U̶R̶  boss fight. I know the reference is only having his name crossed out, but, I mean, it's cool. Furthermore, I especially enjoyed the Prime Sanctum boss fights so far, and I'm excited to see what P-3 is. I just pray that it's not another gauntlet fight like P-2. Anyways, speaking of P-2, I liked the involvement of Sisyphus into the game's story. It's very similar to Dante's Inferno, where he uses Greek and Roman characters to make a Christian narrative. Overall, I really liked this game, it reminds me of a lot of different games that I've played and incorporates those elements wonderfully. Anyways, if you took the time to read this, thank you. Have a good day.

This game is like doom eternal on crack. 
If you at all like doom eternal than ultrakill is just the game to scratch that itch, it offers even more intense FPS combat than doom ever did and it did not devolve into the utter nonsense the endgame of doom eternal gets into with the DLC levels and master levels. Looking at you Mars core master level. The skill ceiling here is significantly higher than doom eternal but it is far more rewarding. To get the most out of ultrakill and unlock some of the hardest bosses in gaming you have to engage in a delicate yet strict ballet of death. Twisting weapons around, scattering a shotgun boost here, a saw trap here, all while avoiding death and balancing your health and weapon cooldown. Masterfully crafted.

Ultrakill is the most enjoyable fps I have played, recently.... no ever. The one I enjoy the most and I am not even that much into that genre. But as I played it it turned out more than just fps but a ccaptivating game with interesting storyline and lore. And I love to find out more as the game will near it's completion.
I would like to start my enjoyment with the fast paced play trhough as if it wasn't mentioned berforre lol but really my adhd brain loves it fr.
The enemies have amazing designs and good how do you say in fancy words I like how they are behaving? Their A.I. They are very unique and enjoyable enemies to fight. Honorable mentions: Gabriel, V2, Swordmachine, Maurice, Ferryman
The spoundtracts are amaying and I love to listen to the outside the game as well.

I also love drawing the characters and I have been hyperfixating a lot on this game. IOt brings me a lot of joy and whenever I do something cool in game it feels rrewarding and earned as well. I feel proud of my progress. I am not the best player but I still do feel very happy and pround of overcoming the challanges of the game. Sucha as getting perfect ranks, Getting better at difficulties I wasn't originally good at, fighting bosses, etc.

There are few weapons but you can get very creative with the usage and you get tips as you progress foward. I am not good at all ultratricks and using everything but I am still honning my skills. The variety of wewapons is very satisying and you will not get bored nor felt that the weapons are lacking. Sorry I am  not weapon expers but I enjoy marksman a lot. Tosses a coin towards you.

I definitely recomend this to people who love challenges and even if you aren't that good like me you can play on easier difficulty and enjoy the plot a lot too. I can see many reasons you can like this game. Or even if you aren't that fps gamer like I was.

I also found about this game thgrough seeing it around youtube and I recognised the publisher since I played their other game. They seem to found many talented developers and I don't regret giving this game a try!!!!

Ultrakill is not a game I would have played were it not for friends convincing me it was worth it.
 I usually don't like "Doom clones", never was a fan of Quake, and I dislike having a style meter tell me what to do.
This my favorite game in the last 5 years by no small margin. Despite it being basically the sum of all my least favorite categories. 

There is so much love being poured into by Hakita and PITR, and in every moment, pixel, sound effect, and note of the soundtrack, you can tell you're playing something that was made intentionally and passionately.

I got this game just after P-2 came out, watching my friend suffer through it, and it was that moment I decided it looked like fun, I like hard games after all. Hard cut to  almost 100 hours later, having P ranked every level and sanctum, I think it's safe to say I ended up liking it after all. Sisyphus was the initial draw to get me to try this game in the first place, so in his own words, "I don't regret a second of it."

At first I gave it a good review, but the further you go the worse it gets. This game advertises itself like Quake x DMC, but this game has NOTHING to do with dmc. Ranking is absolutely broken, prioritizing time in air and multi kills over actual style. Coin counters, parries, intricate weapon combos are... useless. Just try to mash space and ctrl and blow shit up around you and dont forget to parry your shotgun shot for 99999th time, surely this will never get boring) In DmC, Bayonetta, most action games you just play good, try not taking much damage and this is enough for game to reward your skill with high ranking. But ooooh boy Ultrakill is not the case. Here if you want to get good rank YOU HAVE TO FOLLOW DEVS RULES. Hop around like idiot and dont even try to do something fun, you will die and the whole mission will be ruined. And yeah switching fists is questionable mechanic to say the least but maybe author plans to expand upon it, if not, this is useless, just combine two arms in one. And instadeath when falling or touching environmental hazards is absolutely ridiculous, there is no a single argument in support of it. Good thing that this is early access, fixing things i listed here shouldnt be too much of a hustle

Here's what makes this different from other boomer shooters. 
1. Every level is monstrously different from the last, keeping it fresh the whole way. 
2. The parry mechanic is incredible satisfying
3. The fact that the only way to heal is to punch an enemy in the face
4. VERY fun

Only cons that I really noticed:
1. Bosses are VERY difficult. Sometimes prohibitively difficult, and seem out of place compared to the levels that came before. 
2. The game is new, but looks like it's ready for a remaster. I know it's a style choice and allows for higher FPS, but sometimes it's hard to see where you're going or understand what you're seeing on screen. It lacks a little clarity.

Simply a must-play for any self respecting trans person. No pumpkins though, which is a shame. I think it took me around 20 hours to really learn to love how different this game was. I got it because a friend of mine said I should play it and I had fun with it but i kinda dropped it after finishing act 1 because of the difficulty spike. I think at the time I had probably only played for about a dozen hours or so. However, now that I've given it a second shot I have to say that this is one of my very few 10/10 games.
I enjoy how versatile the weapons are, The art direction is phenomenal, the music is very fitting for the pacing, and I love the religious motifs the game uses. It's still early access at time of writing so things are subject to change but you really should give it a shot!

Edit [1/22/2024]:
I wanted to make this edit just to add a few thoughts now that I have a bit more experience. The first layer of act 3 came out pretty recently and I'll be honest, at first I really didn't like it. I felt the same with pretty much all of act 2 recently. As I said earlier, that difficulty spike is killer but I noticed something interesting. Ultrakill has a unique level ranking system based on overall style (how varied and impressive your kills are), time, and enemies killed. If you achieve a perfect score (S rank) in all 3 categories without dying you achieve a P (or perfect) rank on the level. This is completely optional and is mostly an added challenge for players. That being said, going out of my way to P rank every level actually increased my enjoyment. It forced me to learn and adapt to new strategies to overcome challenges. While some of these are much harder than others to P rank, I really do recommend it if you're just not enjoying the game. It might seem odd to purposefully make the game harder for yourself, but trust me it'll make the game click with you so much faster. I also highly recommend looking up guides for weapon techniques and interactions. The sky's the limit here, and there's no shame in asking for help.


TL:DR
Ultrakill is fun when you challenge yourself. Going out of your way to learn weird mechanics really does improve your enjoyment even if it seems difficult and counter intuitive. It's alright to take your time learning how to get faster so don't be afraid to ask for help.

Its absolutely amazing, the sheer depth of its gameplay combined with a stunning presentation still has me hooked. It has an expansive combat system that is easy to learn and simple on the surface but gives you endless options on playstyle and tech, creating a skill ceiling which ascends beyond the stars. It's been a year and I'm still learning tech, despite there being a small simple arsenal of set weapons. The campaign is amazing, every level built with unique creativity and inspiration, they are linear but engaging, with constant new ideas and great arena design utilising the enemies to create arenas that are fun even when replaying them over and over. The enemies are distinct and reactive, having many ways they respond and can interact with the players actions. The thematic presentation is extremely varied and never boring, expressing ideas and themes with stark  imaginative set pieces that are fun to play through and(Mixed with the soundtrack that is absolutely phenomenal at expressing said themes and being an absolute banger) are fantastic to view and explore. The levels are the definition of quality over quantity, every one unique and fun. The game is also quite challenging, but has a lot of settings to allow the player to customise how they wish to play and their preferences, but the challenge and encouragement for perfection makes the game infinitely replayable. Its still one of my favourite games, def recommended.

Ok so this isn't the greatest game ever made. Is it amazing? Yes, BUT it's not complete. It's superb but kinda lacks content at the moment, it is in early access at the moment after all. It's a hard game, and there's no shame in turning down the difficulty. But once you've P ranked everything you want to P rank without grinding there's nothing really to do. If you're like me and don't really like doing the same speedrun over and over again, or just grinding out the same level in order to P rank it, then once you've done the main game and a bit of the cyber grind, there's not a lot to do. I did the game in lenient, call me a casual idc I get a lot of shit for it anyway but I've beaten every level and I'm not into trying to be the best out of my friends, if you're super competitive then I'm sure you'll love that stuff, but if you're not, like me, it's not the greatest game ever made. I'd recommend getting it in a bundle with Turbo Overkill. It's another amazing movement shooter. Get that bundle instead of this by itself. Cheers, Ym

OK but seriously, this is the most innovative and addicting FPS I have ever had the absolute pleasure of playing. I will admit, there is a a big learning curve (I guess its optional but its fun as hell). The community is absolute dogshit, and I would advise not interacting with them for the first dozen or so hours you will inevitably sink into the game. If you want to see how far the rabithole of ridiculous tech goes, go on YouTube and watch people dive into it. I recommend watching Herb Messiah's videos: most importantly, his video on coin mechanics.

DO NOT NEGLECT THE COIN! It is by far the most versatile and powerful weapon in the game, but it requires LOTS of practice. Once you know how to pull of some of the crazy tech, it starts to become muscle memory. Levels stop being challenges and morph into bloody sandboxes. 

Be sure to be as stylish as you possibly can, it appeases your audience.

A friend of mine recommended this and its consuming me now. I consider myself to be rather bad at games, and still managed to have loads of fun, this game is also actively forcing me to get better because I WANT to get the best rank on every level, I WANT to find every secret, I want to see myself improve and how this story will go. I highly recommend this game, I could not possibly recommend this game enough. And don't let people taking about how it's hard turn you off! It certainly can be, no doubt, but there's tons of settings and difficulties you can mess around with until you find what's right for you. And tons of ways to play, I've greatly enjoyed finding a too tough boss and then trying to go at it my own way and then actually succeeding. Overall the game is wonderful and my need to see the world, the story, and then to see myself improve because I actually feel I could keeps me going through it. Definitely give the demo a try at least! I played through every main mission that currently exists, mostly getting a solid D rank on everything, had loads of fun, then went secret hunting, and am only now ah, actually trying to get better. I cannot wait to see what the rest of this game brings as more comes out!

It definitely can get frustrating at times, I skimmed over that fact a bit, but honestly, it took me a quite awhile to truly genuinely get frustrated, which left me feeling pleasantly surprised!

Also there's controller support and its awesome I love it dearly as someone who is far far more used to controller than keyboard and mouse

The violence layer was quite the difficulty spike for me, I'm scared to try, but I hope one day I get good at that too

this is the very first shooter game ive ever played. i didnt grow up with doom or... uh, any of the other ones. i think going in completely blind and totally empty on the "how do i shoot?" front made the experience better, actually. i got to build up my skills naturally and get better over time, and theres no better feeling than realizing that after a few days of practice, you can melt bosses that took you hours to gun down the first time.

i would recommend this to anyone, except for people that believe violence isn't an answer.

My review of Ultrakill.

Pros:
The best video game combat I've experienced, like ever. Not that I play a lot of games.
Every layer is unique and interesting, be it lore, level design or visual aesthetic.
Great weapon arsenal, where every one has a use and is viable in some way. (except for alt marksmen)
Amazing voice acting, even though there isn't a lot of it.

Cons:
Some of the earlier levels don't hold up well when compared to the later ones. (not that they're bad)
Lust is my least favorite layer. While the visual aesthetic is great and the lore implications are cool, the level design really can be infuriating sometimes, especially for P-ranks. (likely a skill issue on my part)
Hakita has recently stated in an interview that he's planning on visually upgrading limbo and gluttony, but I think lust could use some love, since I think it has yet to reach its full potential.
