And here is my experience opinion on ULTRAKILL:
I first met ULTRAKILL is on YouTube. I saw plenty of people saying the game is good but I didn't even those videos. I saw the graphic of this game and like: I am not a retro fan so I will pass. Some while later, I got bored and came back to this game asking myself: why don't I give this boomer shooter a try and see if it's worth it? (It did.)
In my memory, I did watch the trailer and a few reviews like 'using fist to parry is so cool'  but I prefer trying instead of reading so I didn't care that much. My only thought that time is the music is quite intense. Although I don't mind spoilers, I intentionally avoid any information of the game before I finished act 1 for my experience of trying the game(on standard). It caused that I just use a variety of each weapon. I was using only red revolver, green short gun, green nail gun and blue railcannon. According to order: funny spinny gun, faster reload and more damage, decent burst damage and tons of damage. It is a fast paced game and sliding goes: Weeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeee! 
Using blood for healing source. The blood and gore from killing enemies make my whole scene red giving me dopamine. I was already satisfied  and enjoy this game so much. Well, looking back now, I did suffer a lot that time. Since it is almost 6 months, I don't remember clearly how I thought that time but mostly it should be this is quite fun.(1) 
                                                       The most memorable moment of act 1:
1-4 where we meet V2, which is a classic 'I am you but stronger', is suppose to be a skill check for the player. As the play style I mentioned above, I did struggle to beat V2. V2 constantly moving make non-marksman (green revolver) revolver hard to aim and overheat nail gun required warm up, by the time I got the alt fire, V2 was going away from me or already far away from me. The rail cannon was not available that time. Not good enough to parry a.k.a. skill issue. The only option left is my shotgun which only required a moment of close up to deal damage.However, I am still lacking of damage. Until I accidentally overpumped it 3 times, the damage is significantly high but to both of us. It is almost 1/3 of V2's health. Then, my first technique was formed [overpump explosion -> point blink shotgun for blood to heal] x3. The execution still got me died, died a lot. I ended up with 50-60 restart in around an hour for my first victory against V2.
2-2 where you get the railcannon, the most powerful weapon.
2-4 where you can parry a giant. 'Rules of Nature'.
3-1, in the last room, I spammed parrying when I was panic. Somehow I manage to parry a red orb into the crowd and got the style meter to Ultrakill, which is the highest rank. It was my first time and I knew I just got lucky but it still felt like getting approved from someone you approve.
3-2 where the first encounter of Gabriel happens. The voice acting is exquisite. I found he was easier than V2. (not  complaining) Although Gabriel hit harder and faster, he does not move constantly as V2. It makes him has longer windows for me to attack. Maybe because of the room size, I can just spam slide to dodge most of the attacks.
End of act 1.

Then, I went to check about how to play the game. A door to a new world was opened. First of all, use more guns. Guns in this game got lots of combos. Most varieties of guns of most of shooters are just different with the numbers, you just find one is suitable and leave others alone and they just do their own jobs in their own situation. I am not saying there is no other games did this but ULTRAKILL is the most and the best so far I have seen.

                                                    View of Weapons before and after I took a peek to those tech
Revolvers:
Blue: (Before) meh, a pretty decent starter weapon.
          (After) better than red in opened area. Also, heard of slap?
Green: (Before) why would I aim a coin when I can aim directly?
            (After)the coins follow your inertia so actually there is no aiming requirement and the coins can combo with any hit-scan weapon (even enemies).
Red: (Before) cool funny spinny gun.
        (After) good in closed area but I should use more my arsenal.
Shotguns:
Swap to totally ignore any reload time.
Projectile boost.
Blue: (Before) has grenade but slow as fuck.
          (After) grenade can combo with any hit-scan weapon to increase explosion to even nuke. (Start using frequently after P-1)
Green: (Before) good gun.
            (After) can even use i-frame to prevent self-damaging, better gun. 
Nail guns:
Blue: (Before) faster normal fire rate but I like overheat burst more.
          (After) can to some weird stuff with the magnet but brain dead nails spam goes bruuuuuuuuuuuuuh.
Green: (Before) I like it but it has shorter range and required warm up.
            (After) can use blue one to gain overheat almost instantly, brain dead spam let's go.
Rail cannons:
Blue: (Before) tons of damage.
          (After) oh, no head shot but can reflect the huge ass laser multiple times for multi-'tons of damage'.
Red: (Before) explosive but I prefer blue.
        (After) MASS DESTRUCTION.
Green: (Before) get blood? I would rather just kill it.
            (After) can be punched to another enemy... Noted.

Well, there are many more tech and combos of the arsenal I can't just list them all out. Here are just my views as example to show this game is far better than I expected.
Not only arsenal, this game also gets many tech on movement, slam storage, dash storage, supper jump, b-hopping and more. This game got so much to learn. More importantly, so much to play.
(I still  struggle instant rocket ride, SKILL ISSUE.)
After some learning, I went P-ranking in act to reclaim myself. After that, it is time for act 2.

                                                      Views of act 2:
4-1 where power up is introduced, I can have a right arm on both side
4-2 where now I can have 2 right arm on both side
4-3 darkness means less vision means less power, this is a power fantasy game but it is ULTRAKILL so I accepted. Also, fuck something wicked prank.
4-4 final battle with V2. Cool sliding chasing fight and little brother give me a hand, again.
5-1 water.
5-2 time requirement is higher, time to improve my movement.
5-3 rocket and time to improve my combat skills.
5-4 no special thought but first time seeing others do a totally air-bone fight is so cool.
6-1 Gabriel call me earlier this time. Fancy meet you here.
6-2 Gabriel as exquisite as he should be.

Moreover, the Prime Sanctums levels are so challenging and bring so much satisfaction for P-ranking or just finishing. The moment I found myself to parry Minos attack automatically by my reflex felt so good. They made me better at parry not surprisingly.

Violence, the 7th layer is out by this Christmas. I did think this game can be better again.
                                                     Views of Violence:
7-1 the light mode is still shocking, train fight is cool like 4-4 but I am getting chase now.
7-2 giant bomb
7-3 spooky blood tree
7-4 I see someone thinks it is cool but my first image is just ' Why my rico shot not hitting? It is right in front of me and I am like stunned.'
Pretty good job so far.

Alright, listen up, fellow gaming chads. Ultrakill is the epitome of unfiltered, balls-to-the-wall action. I'm talking about a game that throws you into a whirlwind of pixelated chaos and demands you flex those gaming muscles.

The arsenal? It's not just guns; it's a symphony of destruction. You've got weapons that make you feel like a digital Schwarzenegger, obliterating anything in your path. And the movement? It's not about walking; it's about breakneck speed, double-jumping, and acrobatics that would make any action hero jealous.

Enemies? They swarm you like you're the last keg at a frat party. It's a relentless onslaught that separates the chads from the noobs. And the levels? They're like mazes of carnage, filled with secrets to discover and surprises to conquer.

Let's talk aesthetics – pixel art nostalgia on steroids. It's like gaming in a time machine, and it's glorious. The soundtrack? It's not just music; it's the heartbeat of your epic rampage. Every beat syncs with your every move, creating a symphony of destruction that gets the testosterone pumping.

Story? Who cares? Ultrakill isn't about plot twists; it's about flexing those gaming reflexes and leaving a trail of pixelated destruction. If you're a hardcore gamer who thrives on intensity, if you want a game that's a workout for your thumbs and your ego, Ultrakill is your VIP ticket to gaming nirvana. Rip and tear, chads – this one's for us! 🚀💪🎮

NEVERMIND THEY JUST ADDED IT

If you like fast movement, fast-paced gameplay, or if you enjoy FPS games, or if you like games, GIVE THIS GAME A SHOT (there is a free demo if you don't want to buy the game yet). It's perfect in almost every way. When you finish Act One, you may feel like you are worse than what the game intended, but THAT'S PART OF IT BECAUSE IT FORCES YOU TO LEARN INSTEAD OF JUST RANDOMLY SHOOTING. It's really good, is what I'm trying to say. (It doesn't force you to use specific guns, but it tries to ease you into it and 'convince' you to use that weapon in that situation.)

The only downside of this game is that you need to have experience with a mouse because it requires a lot of good aiming, though you can use auto-aim (built-in) at around 10 percent or something.

Actual Review: This game is just amazing. Prelude and early Act I might be a bit easy if you've had experience in the genre but even then, it's still a fun game due to the experimentation you can do in those areas. Act II was extremely fun except for 5-3 in my opinion... until it brought in the S.M.S Rocket Launcher or whatever it's called. That weapon was so fun to mess around with, especially when I learned about being able to ride the rockets. Act III isn't fully done but Layer 7 was so cool, I won't say it wasn't fun because I was just having a skill issue. The soundtrack is way too good for it's own good. I wanna get good times but the music keeps making me wanna stay longer so i can listen to it. Especially P-1's Minos Prime music [Order] and the Requiem motif. P-2 was an insane challenge but it felt so good when I completed it, I have no idea how I've P ranked it with just 27 hours on the game. There's so many insane mechanics I can use like Railcoining, Nuking, and really anything with the coins. I haven't played all the secret levels and I won't say anything about them since they aren't required and are better when experienced blind. 10/10 Please play.
